  "course_description": "Seminar or lecture series on topics of anthropological interest at an intermediate level. Maybe repeated for credit when topic varies.",
  "course_notes": "The term \"psychological anthropology\" contains many different facets. What unites them is the effort to integrate the understanding of the individual (the area covered by osychology) with the anthropological study of collectives - cultures and societies, or \"sociocultural systems\". In this course the focus will be on ethnographic descriptions of childhood, parenting, and the way culture is learned by young humans in different societies; and on theoretical approaches by which we try to make sense of these processes. A key problematic to be addressed concerns the fact that most (though not all!) psychological theorizing and explanation is done by modern, Western investigators using data collected from the observation of, and experiments on, modern, Western people. Anthropology asks us to consider how enculturation, socialization, and learning are understood and practiced in a wide range of non-Western societies. We will see that these processes vary widely, throwing into question the validity of many concepts and theories in the current field of psychology. This course aims to shed some cross-cultural light on the question of how such construction takes place through the creation of new generations of enculturated and socialized members of the varied sociocultural systems in which they pass their lives. It is not without significance that students in this class will not only study these processes, but are also themselves experiencing them.",
